learning_outcomes.description: Critically engage with consumer and carer perspectives in mental health practice.
Analyse the regulatory and professional structures governing mental health practice in Australia, including emerging ethical challenges related to digital and AI-mediated practice.
Analyse and apply ethical principles to dilemmas and challenges in mental health practice.
Develop and defend ethically sound systems, policies, and safeguards in mental health practice.

assessments.task_description:
Students will complete a written report based on an interview with a consumer or carer who has engaged with mental health, psychotherapy, counselling, or art therapy services. The purpose of the task is to explore real experiences of care, including examples of both respectful/effective and less helpful practices, and to reflect on the implications for ethical, person-centred practice. The report must demonstrate sensitive engagement with the interviewee, integrate their narrative meaningfully, and include a structured personal reflection on the learning gained from the interview process.

Students must attach a signed consent form in Appendix A, confirming the interviewee understood the purpose of the interview and agreed to participate. Students must also include original interview notes in Appendix B, in order to support academic integrity and authorship.

Word limit: 1,500 words (+/- 10%)

assessments.assessment_title: Ethical Decision-Making Framework: Application & Critical Reflection Essay
assessments.task_description:
Length: 2,500 words (+/- 10%, excluding appendix)

Students will prepare a written essay in two parts that develops an individual ethical decision-making framework for mental health practice and critically reflects on the use of this framework in conjunction with generative artificial intelligence (AI). The task is designed to deepen students’ understanding of ethical theory, professional values, and real-world decision-making processes, while also encouraging critical evaluation of the emerging role of AI in mental health practice.

PART 1: Ethical Framework Development

Students will conduct a literature review drawing on ethical theory, professional codes, regulatory expectations, and relevant mental health ethics literature. Using this evidence base, students will develop and justify a personalised ethical decision-making framework tailored to their professional identity and therapeutic context. The framework should be original, theoretically supported, and structured as a practical step-by-step model for guiding future ethical decisions in mental health practice.

PART 2: Applied Reflection & AI Analysis

Students will apply their ethical framework to a hypothetical ethical dilemma provided in the course and will input their framework into a generative AI tool to explore how AI interprets, applies, or distorts their model. Students will then critically analyse the strengths, limitations, and ethical risks associated with AI-mediated decision making, including potential issues around bias, confidentiality, professional judgement, clinical nuance, and client safety. Students will conclude this section with a reflective statement articulating their professional position on whether, when, and how AI could be ethically incorporated into mental health practice.

Appendix Requirement:

All AI prompts and AI-generated outputs must be submitted in an appendix. Students must clearly distinguish their own ideas, interpretation, and reasoning within the essay from any AI-generated material. Failure to include prompts/output may result in academic penalty.

assessments.task_description:
Across Weeks 7–10, students will participate in Ethical Practice Tutorials designed to explore how ethical principles translate into real-world mental health work. Each student will be assigned to one tutorial week in which they will contribute to the teaching process by presenting a short, de-identified practice case example that illustrates the ethical theme for that week. For their allocated week, students will briefly outline the case, highlight the relevant ethical principles drawn from the assigned readings, and engage in a tutor-led Q&A discussion to demonstrate understanding and application of ethical ideas.

While only the allocated week is formally assessed, all students are encouraged to contribute to discussions across the tutorial series to support an interactive and collegial learning environment.

Assessment will consider:

• the clarity and relevance of the case example to the ethical theme

• demonstrated integration of core readings and ethical theory

• ability to engage with questions and discussion in their allocated week

Confidentiality requirement:

All case material must be fully de-identified and free of information that could reasonably identify clients, settings, or organisations. Composite cases may be used where necessary to protect confidentiality.

assessments.task_description:
Ethical mental health practice requires proactive planning and preventative safeguards to reduce the likelihood of future ethical dilemmas. For this assessment students will design an original ethical safeguard (e.g., clinical guideline, policy or structured protocol) relevant to their area of mental health practice. The safeguard should reflect the student's own original thinking and be informed by relevant ethical theory, professional codes and research evidence.

Students will present their safeguard to the class in a brief 10-minute presentation, outlining:

  • the ethical issue or context the safeguard addresses,
  • the rationale underpinning their guideline or policy, and
  • important limitations, caveats, and implementation considerations.


Following the presentation, students will engage in a 5-minute Q&A, responding to questions about the conceptual basis, applicability, and ethical reasoning underpinning their safeguard. The Q&A is designed to strengthen authorship security and give students the opportunity to demonstrate genuine understanding of the ethical and practical implications of their proposed safeguard.
